quizzes.question:
What is the largest number that will be printed by this code?
for (int x = 1; x < 8; x++) {
  if (x > 5)
    break;
  Console.WriteLine(x);
}

quizzes.textContent:
[h1]break[/h1]

We saw the use of [b]break [/b]in the switch statement.
Another use of [b]break [/b]is in loops: When the [b]break [/b]statement is encountered inside a loop, the loop is immediately terminated and the program execution moves on to the next statement following the loop body.
[b]For example:[/b] [code format="cs" codeId="845"]int num = 0;
while (num < 20)
{
   if (num == 5)
     [b]break;[/b]

   Console.WriteLine(num);
   num++;
}

/* Outputs:
0
1
2
3
4
*/[/code]
[note]If you are using nested loops (i.e., one loop inside another loop), the [b]break [/b]statement will stop the execution of the innermost loop and start executing the next line of code after the block.[/note]

